[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'larger proprietary models and a lot more. So, let\'s jump right in. First up, this AI is pretty cool. It\'s called Vox Hammer, and this allows you to microedit 3D models. It\'s basically an editor that'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can change specific parts of a 3D object while keeping the rest of the object the same. So, here are some examples. Here are a few objects and the user would specify the region to edit using a mask'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then enter either a text prompt or a reference image which describes the edit and it will magically change that area only while keeping the rest of the object the same. And you can apply the'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit using a text prompt or a reference image. For example, if on the left is your original model, well, you can prompt it to be a stone crab and it will change the shell into stone. Or here\'s a'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'diner with a big balloon and here is what you get. Or here\'s a bowl of bread and indeed it adds this bread inside the bowl. Or here\'s another example where we'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can change this bowl of apples into oranges like this. Now instead of just a text prompt, you can also upload a reference image to edit the object. So, for example, if this is your original 3D'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model and then you upload this image where this part is different, well, it\'ll automatically apply the edit to your 3D model. Or here\'s another example where we can change the swords into'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'roses via this reference image like this. Or we can also change this chimney into an apple using this reference image. And here is what you get. Or here we can turn this character into a panda'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like this. So now it\'s super easy to edit 3D models. You can just take a screenshot of your model and then plug it into any image editor and then edit whichever part you want and then plug it through this AI to automatically apply'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the edits to your 3D model. And Vox Hammer uses what they call part aare object editing. So it\'s first able to segment the model into meaningful parts and then only apply the edits to the'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parts that you specify. And this preserves the rest of the model and keeps it consistent. Anyways, if you scroll up to the top of the page, the nice thing is they\'ve released the code and the models already. So, if you click'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into this GitHub repo and you scroll down a bit, this contains all the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. However, note that here it says you do need an Nvidia GPU with at least 40 GB of VRAM.'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In fact, they even add that 80 GB is strongly recommended. Anyways, all the links are up here. So, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'below. Next up, this AI is super useful for image generation. So, it\'s called Compass. And this is essentially a Laura or a fine-tune, which you can add on top of an existing image generator like flux'

[03:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or stable diffusion. And the purpose of compass is to help the image generator improve the spatial arrangement of objects in your image. So, here are some examples. If your prompt includes bird'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'below skateboard, well, without compass, if you\'re using flux, for example, it\'s almost impossible to get the bird to show up below the skateboard because that\'s just very abnormal and unexpected'

[04:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'place. So, it just tends to generate images with a bird on a skateboard. However, with compass, notice that it can now accurately generate the bird below the skateboard like you specified.'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Or here\'s another example. If you try to get Flux to generate a bear on the right of a truck, notice that with just the regular Flux model, it completely fails to generate a bear on the right of a'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'truck. It tends to give you images like this. But after adding compass, notice that for all generations, it indeed generates a bear to the right of a truck. Or here\'s a laptop above a dog. And as you can see for the generations'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'without compass generating a dog using a laptop whereas after adding compass for all generations it\'s actually adding a laptop above the dog. So this tool is way better at getting the AI model to'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
